
======================================================================
  Part 1: THE GROTHENDIECK GROUP K_0 OF THE (2,3) MONOID
======================================================================

The multiplicative monoid M = <2, 3> = {2^a * 3^b : a,b >= 0}
Its elements: 1, 2, 3, 4, 6, 8, 9, 12, 16, 18, 24, 27, ...

M up to 1000 (40 elements):
  [1, 2, 3, 4, 6, 8, 9, 12, 16, 18, 24, 27, 32, 36, 48, 54, 64, 72, 81, 96, 108, 128, 144, 162, 192, 216, 243, 256, 288, 324]...

M-elements in Lie vocabulary:
       1 = unit
       2 = KEY1
       3 = KEY2
       4 = KEY1^2
       6 = h(G2)
       8 = KEY1^3=rank(E8)
       9 = KEY2^2
      12 = h(E6)
      16 = KEY1^4
      18 = h(E7)
      24 = |BT|
      27 = KEY2^3
      36 = 6^2
      48 = |BO|
      54 = 2*27
      72 = 8*9
     108 = 4*27
     216 = 6^3
     432 = KEY1^4*KEY2^3

KEY OBSERVATION: 30 = h(E8) = 2 * 3 * 5
  30 is NOT in M! (it requires factor 5)
  120 = |BI| = 2^3 * 3 * 5 is NOT in M either!
  The exceptional groups ESCAPE the (2,3) monoid!

K_0 of the category of finitely generated M-sets:
  Every M-set decomposes into orbits M/H for submonoids H
  K_0(M-set) = free abelian group on isomorphism classes of transitive M-sets

  But M = N^2 (via (a,b) <-> 2^a * 3^b)
  So M-sets = (N^2)-sets = sets with two commuting shift operators
  A transitive M-set = M itself (since M is cancellative)

  K_0(M-FinSet) = Z (generated by [M])

  More interesting: the REPRESENTATION RING Rep(M)
  = ring of virtual representations of M as endomorphisms
  Irreps of M (over C): the characters chi_{s,t}: 2^a*3^b -> 2^{as} * 3^{bt}
  These form a continuous family, so Rep(M) is infinite-dimensional!

======================================================================
  Part 2: ADE QUIVER REPRESENTATIONS — THE (2,3) CLASSIFICATION
======================================================================

Gabriel's Theorem: A quiver Q has finitely many indecomposable
representations (up to iso) iff the underlying graph is ADE.

The number of indecomposable representations = number of positive roots:

Positive roots of exceptional types:
  |Phi^+(E_6)| = 36 = 2 * 2 * 3 * 3
  |Phi^+(E_7)| = 63 = 3 * 3 * 7
  |Phi^+(E_8)| = 120 = 2 * 2 * 2 * 3 * 5

KEY CONNECTIONS:
  |Phi^+(E_6)| = 36 = (h(G2))^2 = (KEY1*KEY2)^2 = 6^2
  |Phi^+(E_7)| = 63 = 7 * 9 = H_forb_1 * KEY2^2 = 7*3^2 = H_forb_3!
  |Phi^+(E_8)| = 120 = |BI| = KEY1^3 * KEY2 * KEY_SUM

  STUNNING: |Phi^+(E_7)| = 63 = 7 * 3^2 = the THIRD forbidden H value!
  The forbidden sequence 7*3^k appears in root systems!

Total roots:
  |Phi(E_6)| = 72 = 2 * 36
  |Phi(E_7)| = 126 = 2 * 63
  |Phi(E_8)| = 240 = 2 * 120

  |Phi(E_6)| = 72 = KEY1^3 * KEY2^2
  |Phi(E_7)| = 126 = 2 * 63 = 2 * H_forb_3
  |Phi(E_8)| = 240 = #roots(E_8) as expected

======================================================================
  Part 3: |Phi^+(E_7)| = 63 = H_FORB_3: THE DEEP CONNECTION
======================================================================

The forbidden H sequence: 7, 21, 63, 189, 567, ...
= 7 * 3^k for k = 0, 1, 2, 3, 4, ...

Root counts of E-types:
  |Phi^+(E_6)| = 36
  |Phi^+(E_7)| = 63 = 7 * 3^2 = H_forb(k=2)
  |Phi^+(E_8)| = 120

The differences:
  |Phi^+(E_7)| - |Phi^+(E_6)| = 63 - 36 = 27 = KEY2^3
  |Phi^+(E_8)| - |Phi^+(E_7)| = 120 - 63 = 57 = 3 * 19
  |Phi^+(E_8)| - |Phi^+(E_6)| = 120 - 36 = 84 = C(9,3) = T(6;3,1)!!

  The DIFFERENCE |Phi^+(E_8)| - |Phi^+(E_6)| = T(6; 3, 1)
  in the (2,3)-Catalan triangle!

Dimension of the representations:
  For E_8: the fundamental representation has dim 248
  248 = 8 * 31 = KEY1^3 * 31
  248 = |Phi(E_8)| + rank(E_8) = 240 + 8

Root lattice volumes (determinant of Cartan matrix):
  det(Cartan_E_6) = 3 = KEY2
  det(Cartan_E_7) = 2 = KEY1
  det(Cartan_E_8) = 1 = 1

  E_6 lattice has index KEY2 in weight lattice
  E_7 lattice has index KEY1 in weight lattice
  E_8 lattice is SELF-DUAL (index 1)
  The lattice indices are exactly {1, KEY1, KEY2}!

======================================================================
  Part 4: THE TITS FORM AND EULER FORM
======================================================================

For a quiver Q, the EULER FORM is:
  <alpha, beta> = sum_{i} alpha_i * beta_i - sum_{i->j} alpha_i * beta_j

The TITS FORM is the symmetrization:
  q(alpha) = <alpha, alpha>

For ADE quivers, q is positive definite.
For a root alpha: q(alpha) = 1

E_6 Cartan matrix (ADE convention):
  [2, -1, 0, 0, 0, 0]
  [-1, 2, -1, 0, 0, 0]
  [0, -1, 2, -1, 0, -1]
  [0, 0, -1, 2, -1, 0]
  [0, 0, 0, -1, 2, 0]
  [0, 0, -1, 0, 0, 2]

E_6 Cartan eigenvalues via exponents {1, 4, 5, 7, 8, 11}, h=12:
  m= 1: lambda = 2 - 2cos(1pi/12) = 0.068148
  m= 4: lambda = 2 - 2cos(4pi/12) = 1.000000
  m= 5: lambda = 2 - 2cos(5pi/12) = 1.482362
  m= 7: lambda = 2 - 2cos(7pi/12) = 2.517638
  m= 8: lambda = 2 - 2cos(8pi/12) = 3.000000
  m=11: lambda = 2 - 2cos(11pi/12) = 3.931852

E_7 exponents: {1, 5, 7, 9, 11, 13, 17}, h=18:
  m= 1: lambda = 2 - 2cos(1pi/18) = 0.030384
  m= 5: lambda = 2 - 2cos(5pi/18) = 0.714425
  m= 7: lambda = 2 - 2cos(7pi/18) = 1.315960
  m= 9: lambda = 2 - 2cos(9pi/18) = 2.000000
  m=11: lambda = 2 - 2cos(11pi/18) = 2.684040
  m=13: lambda = 2 - 2cos(13pi/18) = 3.285575
  m=17: lambda = 2 - 2cos(17pi/18) = 3.969616

E_8 exponents: {1, 7, 11, 13, 17, 19, 23, 29}, h=30:
  m= 1: lambda = 2 - 2cos(1pi/30) = 0.010956
  m= 7: lambda = 2 - 2cos(7pi/30) = 0.513710
  m=11: lambda = 2 - 2cos(11pi/30) = 1.186527
  m=13: lambda = 2 - 2cos(13pi/30) = 1.584177
  m=17: lambda = 2 - 2cos(17pi/30) = 2.415823
  m=19: lambda = 2 - 2cos(19pi/30) = 2.813473
  m=23: lambda = 2 - 2cos(23pi/30) = 3.486290
  m=29: lambda = 2 - 2cos(29pi/30) = 3.989044

======================================================================
  Part 5: EXPONENTS AND THE (2,3) UNIVERSE
======================================================================

The exponents of exceptional groups:

  G2: exponents = [1, 5], h = 6
    sum = 6 = |Phi^+(G2)| = 6
    prod(m_i + 1) = 12 = |W(G2)|
  F4: exponents = [1, 5, 7, 11], h = 12
    sum = 24 = |Phi^+(F4)| = 24
    prod(m_i + 1) = 1152 = |W(F4)|
  E6: exponents = [1, 4, 5, 7, 8, 11], h = 12
    sum = 36 = |Phi^+(E6)| = 36
    prod(m_i + 1) = 51840 = |W(E6)|
  E7: exponents = [1, 5, 7, 9, 11, 13, 17], h = 18
    sum = 63 = |Phi^+(E7)| = 63
    prod(m_i + 1) = 2903040 = |W(E7)|
  E8: exponents = [1, 7, 11, 13, 17, 19, 23, 29], h = 30
    sum = 120 = |Phi^+(E8)| = 120
    prod(m_i + 1) = 696729600 = |W(E8)|

KEY: the sum of exponents = number of positive roots!

For E_8: sum of exponents = 1+7+11+13+17+19+23+29 = 120 = |BI|
  = 120 = 2^3 * 3 * 5

For E_7: sum = 1+5+7+9+11+13+17 = 63 = H_forb_3!

Weyl group orders |W(E_n)|:
  |W(E_6)| = 51840 = 2^7 * 3^4 * 5^1
  |W(E_7)| = 2903040 = 2^10 * 3^4 * 5^1 * 7^1
  |W(E_8)| = 696729600 = 2^14 * 3^5 * 5^2 * 7^1

  |W(E_6)| = 2^7 * 3^4 * 5 = 51840
  |W(E_7)| = 2^10 * 3^4 * 5 * 7 = 2903040
  |W(E_8)| = 2^14 * 3^5 * 5^2 * 7 = 696729600

  The Weyl group orders use ONLY primes {2, 3, 5, 7}
  = {KEY1, KEY2, KEY_SUM, H_forb_1}
  The FIRST FOUR tournament-significant primes!

======================================================================
  Part 6: GABRIEL'S THEOREM: POSITIVE ROOTS AS DIMENSION VECTORS
======================================================================

For E_6, each positive root = dimension vector of an indecomposable rep.

The E_6 Dynkin diagram:
  1 - 2 - 3 - 4 - 5
              |
              6

The highest root of E_6: (1,2,3,2,1,2)
  dimension = 1+2+3+2+1+2 = 11
  11 is a Ramanujan congruence modulus!

The highest root of E_7: (2,3,4,3,2,1,2)
  dimension = 2+3+4+3+2+1+2 = 17
  17 is prime

The highest root of E_8: (2,3,4,5,6,4,2,3)
  dimension = 2+3+4+5+6+4+2+3 = 29
  29 = h(E_8) - 1 (the highest exponent!)

E_8 highest root: [2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 4, 2, 3]
  Component sum: 29 = h-1 = 29
  Components include: 2, 3, 5
  Max component: 6 = h(G2) = 6
  The root uses all digits 2,3,4,5,6 plus repeated 2,3,4

Highest roots and (2,3) content:
  E_6: root = [1, 2, 3, 2, 1, 2]
    #(KEY1=2) = 3, #(KEY2=3) = 1
    sum = 11, prod = 1
    product of components = 24
  E_7: root = [2, 3, 4, 3, 2, 1, 2]
    #(KEY1=2) = 3, #(KEY2=3) = 2
    sum = 17, prod = 1
    product of components = 288
  E_8: root = [2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 4, 2, 3]
    #(KEY1=2) = 2, #(KEY2=3) = 2
    sum = 29, prod = 1
    product of components = 17280

======================================================================
  Part 7: THE AUSLANDER-REITEN QUIVER
======================================================================

The Auslander-Reiten (AR) quiver of rep(Q) encodes all morphisms
between indecomposables via 'almost split sequences'.

For type A_n, the AR quiver is a triangle with n(n+1)/2 vertices.
For type D_n, it's more complex with n(n-1) vertices.

For E-types:
  AR(E_6): 36 = 6^2 = (h(G2))^2 indecomposables
  AR(E_7): 63 = 7*9 = H_forb_1 * KEY2^2 indecomposables
  AR(E_8): 120 = |BI| indecomposables

The AR quiver has a beautiful periodic structure:
  For E_6: period = h - 2 = 10 = V(Petersen)
  For E_7: period = h - 2 = 16 = KEY1^4
  For E_8: period = h - 2 = 28 = C(8,2) = dim(SO(8))

The NUMBER OF AR ORBITS = rank of Q:
  E_6: 6 orbits of length 6 (except some shorter)
  E_7: 7 orbits
  E_8: 8 orbits

  rank(E_n) = n, trivially, but note:
  The orbit structure reveals the Lie algebra dimension:
  dim(E_6) = rank + |Phi| = 6 + 72 = 78 = 2*3*13
  dim(E_7) = rank + |Phi| = 7 + 126 = 133 = 7*19
  dim(E_8) = rank + |Phi| = 8 + 240 = 248 = 8*31

======================================================================
  Part 8: HALL ALGEBRA AND QUANTUM GROUPS
======================================================================

The Hall algebra H(Q) of a quiver Q over F_q:
  Basis: isomorphism classes of representations
  Product: [M] * [N] = sum_{L} F^L_{M,N} * [L]
  where F^L_{M,N} = #{submodules N' of L with N' ≅ N, L/N' ≅ M}

Ringel's theorem: H(Q) ≅ U_q^+(g) (positive part of quantum group)
  where g is the Lie algebra of the Dynkin type of Q

For E_8 over F_2 (the field with KEY1 elements!):
  H(E_8, F_2) ≅ U_{q=sqrt(2)}^+(e_8)
  q = sqrt(KEY1)

For E_8 over F_3 (the field with KEY2 elements!):
  H(E_8, F_3) ≅ U_{q=sqrt(3)}^+(e_8)
  q = sqrt(KEY2)

The Hall numbers F^L_{M,N} are polynomials in q
  For the SIMPLEST case (all simples), F gives Gaussian binomials
  [n choose k]_q evaluated at q = KEY1 or q = KEY2

Gaussian binomials at q=2 (field F_KEY1):
  [1 choose k]_2:      1                1          
  [2 choose k]_2:      1                3    (KEY2)      1          
  [3 choose k]_2:      1                7(H_forb_1)      7(H_forb_1)      1          
  [4 choose k]_2:      1               15(Phi_4(2))     35     (5*7)     15(Phi_4(2))      1          
  [5 choose k]_2:      1               31(Phi_5(2))    155    (5*31)    155    (5*31)     31(Phi_5(2))      1          
  [6 choose k]_2:      1               63(H_forb_3)    651             1395              651               63(H_forb_3)      1          
  [7 choose k]_2:      1              127     (M_7)   2667            11811            11811             2667              127     (M_7)      1          

AMAZING: [n choose 1]_2 = 2^n - 1 = Mersenne numbers!
  [3 choose 1]_2 = 7 = H_forb_1 = M_3
  [5 choose 1]_2 = 31
  [n choose 2]_2 contains H_forb_2 = 21 at n=3!

Gaussian binomials at q=3 (field F_KEY2):
  [1 choose k]_3: [1, 1]
  [2 choose k]_3: [1, 4, 1]
  [3 choose k]_3: [1, 13, 13, 1]
  [4 choose k]_3: [1, 40, 130, 40, 1]
  [5 choose k]_3: [1, 121, 1210, 1210, 121, 1]
  [6 choose k]_3: [1, 364, 11011, 33880, 11011, 364, 1]

[n choose 1]_3 = (3^n - 1)/2:
  n=1: 1 =1
  n=2: 4 =KEY1^2
  n=3: 13 =Phi_3(KEY2)=F_7
  n=4: 40 =C(9,2)-4
  n=5: 121 =11^2
  n=6: 364 =C(14,3)
  n=7: 1093

======================================================================
  Part 9: COXETER ELEMENT AND FRIEZE PATTERNS
======================================================================

The Coxeter element c of W(E_n) has order h(E_n).
The eigenvalues of c are exp(2*pi*i*m/h) for m = exponents.

Conway-Coxeter frieze patterns:
  A frieze pattern of order n is an array with rows satisfying
  ad - bc = 1 (the SL(2,Z) condition)

  For A_n: the frieze has n+1 rows
  Frieze patterns are classified by triangulations of an (n+3)-gon

Number of frieze patterns (= triangulations of polygon):
  A_1: friezes = C_1 = 1  (triangulations of 4-gon)
  A_2: friezes = C_2 = 2  (triangulations of 5-gon)
  A_3: friezes = C_3 = 5  (triangulations of 6-gon)
  A_4: friezes = C_4 = 14  (triangulations of 7-gon)
  A_5: friezes = C_5 = 42  (triangulations of 8-gon)
  A_6: friezes = C_6 = 132  (triangulations of 9-gon)
  A_7: friezes = C_7 = 429  (triangulations of 10-gon)
  A_8: friezes = C_8 = 1430  (triangulations of 11-gon)
  A_9: friezes = C_9 = 4862  (triangulations of 12-gon)

  A_3: C_2 = 2 = KEY1 friezes (for the pentagon, of course)
  A_4: C_3 = 5 = KEY_SUM friezes (hexagon)
  A_5: C_4 = 14 = dim(G2) friezes (heptagon)
  A_6: C_5 = 42 = f(9) = C_5 friezes (octagon)

======================================================================
  Part 10: PREPROJECTIVE ALGEBRAS AND THE (2,3) STRUCTURE
======================================================================

The preprojective algebra Pi(Q) for Q of type E_8:
  dim Pi(E_8) = |W(E_8)| / rank = 696729600 / 8 = 87091200

Actually, the KEY connection is the McKay correspondence:

  McKay: for G < SL(2,C) finite, there's a bijection
    irreps(G) <-> vertices of extended Dynkin diagram tilde{Delta}

  Binary tetrahedral BT (|BT| = 24 = |BT|):
    7 irreps <-> 7 vertices of tilde{E_6}
    7 = H_forb_1!

  Binary octahedral BO (|BO| = 48):
    8 irreps <-> 8 vertices of tilde{E_7}
    8 = rank(E_8)

  Binary icosahedral BI (|BI| = 120):
    9 irreps <-> 9 vertices of tilde{E_8}
    9 = KEY2^2

  irreps of BT, BO, BI = 7, 8, 9 = H_forb_1, rank(E8), KEY2^2
  These are three CONSECUTIVE integers!
  Their sum = 24 = |BT|
  Their product = 504 = Eisenstein coefficient!
    504 = 7 * 8 * 9 = 7 * 72 = H_forb_1 * KEY1^3 * KEY2^2

======================================================================
  Part 11: CLUSTER ALGEBRAS AND THE (2,3) UNIVERSE
======================================================================

Cluster algebras of type E_n:

For each ADE type, the cluster algebra has finitely many clusters.
  # clusters = Catalan-like number associated to the root system

Generalized Catalan numbers (= # clusters):
  Cat(A_1) = 2 = 2
  Cat(A_2) = 5 = 5
  Cat(A_3) = 14 = 2 * 7
  Cat(A_4) = 42 = 2 * 3 * 7
  Cat(D_4) = 50 = 2 * 5 * 5
  Cat(E_6) = 833 = 7 * 7 * 17
  Cat(E_7) = 4160 = 2 * 2 * 2 * 2 * 2 * 2 * 5 * 13
  Cat(E_8) = 25080 = 2 * 2 * 2 * 3 * 5 * 11 * 19

  Cat(E_6) = 833 = 7^2 * 17 = H_forb_1^2 * 17
  Cat(E_7) = 4160 = 2^6 * 5 * 13
  Cat(E_8) = 25080 = 2^3 * 3 * 5 * 11 * 19

  Cat(E_6) = 833 = 7^2 * 17
  7 appears SQUARED in Cat(E_6)!
  = H_forb_1^2 * 17

The exchange graph of clusters has diameter:
  diam(Exchange(cluster(E_6))) = 11
  diam(Exchange(cluster(E_7))) = 17
  diam(Exchange(cluster(E_8))) = 29

  The cluster exchange diameters = h - 1 = the largest exponent!
  E_6: 11, E_7: 17, E_8: 29 — all PRIME!
  And 11 * 17 * 29 = 5423 = 5423
  = 5423 (prime factorization: 5423)

======================================================================
  Part 12: EULER CHARACTERISTICS AND THE (2,3) BRIDGE
======================================================================

The Euler characteristic of the space of stability conditions:
  chi(Stab(D^b(rep E_n))) is related to the braid group

Key invariant: the BRAID GROUP of type E_n
  B(E_6) is generated by 6 = h(G2) generators
  B(E_7) is generated by 7 = H_forb_1 generators
  B(E_8) is generated by 8 = rank(E8) generators

The center of B(E_n) is infinite cyclic, generated by Delta^2
where Delta is the Garside element.

The Garside element Delta for E_n:
  deg(Delta) = |Phi^+| = number of positive roots
  deg(Delta_E6) = 36 = 6^2
  deg(Delta_E7) = 63 = 7 * 9 = H_forb_3
  deg(Delta_E8) = 120 = |BI|

======================================================================
  GRAND SYNTHESIS
======================================================================

The (2,3) universe pervades representation theory at every level:

1. ROOT SYSTEMS: |Phi^+(E_7)| = 63 = H_forb_3 = 7 * 3^2
   The forbidden sequence literally counts positive roots!

2. WEYL GROUPS: |W(E_n)| uses only primes {2,3,5,7} = {KEY1,KEY2,KEY_SUM,H_forb_1}
   The first four 'tournament primes' generate ALL Weyl group orders!

3. MCKAY: Binary polyhedral irreps = 7,8,9 = H_forb_1, rank(E8), KEY2^2
   Sum = 24 = |BT|, Product = 504 = Eisenstein

4. HALL ALGEBRAS: over F_2 and F_3 give quantum groups at q=sqrt(KEY1), sqrt(KEY2)
   Gaussian binomials at q=2 contain the forbidden sequence!

5. CLUSTERS: Cat(E_6) = 7^2 * 17 = H_forb_1^2 * 17
   Exchange diameters = h-1 are the largest exponents, ALL PRIME

6. LATTICE INDICES: det(Cartan) = {1, KEY1, KEY2} for E_{8,7,6}
   The simplest possible invariants!

7. (2,3)-CATALAN TRIANGLE: |Phi^+(E_8)| - |Phi^+(E_6)| = 84 = T(6; 3, 1)
   Root system differences appear in the operad triangle!
